{"/service/ndnp/vtu/batch_vtu_iceberg_ver01/data/sn86071593/00415628511/1920090201/0435.xml":{"full_text":"THE BRATTLEBOBO DAILY REFORMER; THURSDAY, SEPTEMBER 2, 1920.\ni\nWe Want Your Poultry\nFeed Orders\nEGGS ARE VERY HIGH\nAND ADVANCING and\nwe beg to advise the poultry\nfeeders that while it has\nbeen impossible for nearly a\nyear to obtain OYSTER\nSHELLS, we have at last\npurchased 10 cars and or\ndered them to Brattleboro\nand consumers and dealers\nwill be able to supply their\nwants for the coming year.\nE. CROSBY CO.\nBRATTLEBORO. VT.\nn\nfff\nTHE ALL-YEAR-ROUND\nSOFT DRINK\nEEVO goes especially well with\nlight repasts, buffet lunches,\nchafing dish dainties, fish and\nlobster dishes, chicken dinners,\ncold meats, sausages; cheese\nsandwiches,\" etc.\nALWAYS SERVE IT COLD\nDeWittGroceryCo.\nDistributors\nI When Nature\nWon't\nOur Glasses Will\njGive you natural, comforta\nble vision.\n9\nt\nI he\nNO PROFITEERING\noptometrists)\nBRATTLEBORO, VT.\nTh Largest Optical Establishment\ni in Vermont\nBROOKS\nHOUSE\nG. E. ShermUn\nManager\nFIRE and LIFE\nInsurance\nStrong, Reliable Companiei\n1 Sanford A. Daniels\nCroiby Block, Brattleboro\n\"WANTED\nMen and Women\nFor Hinsdale Tobacco Fields\nTruck leaves station at 6.30\nevery morning\nLOUIS I. ALLEN\nI T 9 PASSENGER t\nI OU 1 S AND BAGGAGE I\nLouis L Allen\nOfflce, Depot News BUnd\ni 'Phone 6S8-W\n5\nPublished Every Evening\nExcept Sunday at\nThe American Building Annex.\nMain Street,\nBrattleboro, Vermont.\nAddreaa AH Communication! to\nThe Reformer.\nTEEMS OF SUBSCRIPTION.\nSingle Copies Three Cents\nOne Week Eighteen Cents\nOne \"Month Seventy-Five Cents\nOne Year Eight Dollars\nEntered in the poatofike at Brattleboro aa\nsecond class natter. 4\nThe Reformer Telephone Number i r\nFor Buaineia Office and Editorial Rooma.\ni TO ADVERTISERS.\nTransient advertising Run, of paper, 50 cents\nan inch for first insertion, 30 cents an inch\nfor each subsequent insertion. Limited space\non urst page at double rates.\nSpace rates on application.\nClassified advertisements Five cents a line\nfirst insertion with 50 per cent discount for\neach subsequent insertion without change of\ncopy. Minimum charge 20 cents. Cash with\norder.\nReading Notices Twenty cents per line first\ninsertion witu su per cent discount tor eacn\nsubsequent insertion without change of copy.\nReading notices are published at foot of local\nitems.\nTO THE SUBSCRIBERS.\nTt is the aim of the management to secure\nefficient service in the delivery of the paper\neach night, and it solicits the co-operation of\nsubscribers to that end. Prompt reports should\nbe given of each failure to receive the paper\non the morning following the omission, in\nperson, by telephone or postal card, thus en\nabling the cause of the error to be promptly\nand accurately discovered and the proper rem\nedy immediately applied. It is only by this\nmethod that the publisher can secure the de\nsired service.\nKember of The Associated Press.\nThe Associated Press Is exclusively en\ntitled to the use for publication of all news\ndespatches credited to it and not otherwise\ncredited in this paper and also the local news\npublished herein.\nThe Reformer is on sale every evening by\nthe following news dealers:\nBrattleboro, Brattleboro News Co., C. W.\nCleaveland, S. L. Purlnton (Esteyville),\nRrnoks House Pharmsev. Allen's Denot News\nstand, George T. Bover, South Main St.\niron uuminrr uisiricw\nWest Brattleboro, J. L. Stocltwell.\nEast Dummerston, M. E. Brown.\nPutney, M. G. Williams.\nNew-fane, N. Af. Batchelder.\nWest Townshend, C H. Grout.\nJamaica, R. J. Daggett.\nSonth Londonderry, F. H. Tyler.\nSouth Vernon, E. B. Buffum.\nNorthfield, Mass., Thompson Bros.\nWest Chesterfield, N. H., Mrs. W. Streeter.\nHinsdale, N. H W. H. Lyman.\nGreenfield, Mass., Greenfield News Co.\nGreenfield, Mass., C. A. Hays.\nTHURSDAY, SEPTEMBER 2, 1920.\nCOX LOSING GROUND.\nWhile it undoubtedly is true people\nlike to see a scrap between politicians,\nthey dislike a nasty and unfair fighter.\nCalling names, boisterous talk or\nrowdyism are not an acceptable sub\nstitute for deserved punishment of a\nbully or a villain, even in a presiden\ntial candidate. Governor Cox in mak\ning his charges against the managers\nof the Republican campaign' apparently'\nassumed the role of a vituperous brag\ngart. The meeting of the senate com\nmittee investigating campaign ex\npenses has completed his downfall.\nGovernor Cox himself could not show a\nshadow of proof for more than half\nof his charges of a $13,000,000 Repub\nlican slush fund but to the investigat\ning committee seeking the facts he\nhas not yet given an iota of evidence, to\nsupport his charges. The acknowledge\nment of Chairman White before the\ncommittee at Chicago yesterday that\nhe had no evidence whatever in behalf\nof the Democratic leader is such a com\nplete discredit that it is pitiful.\nGovernor Cox chose the ground,\nmarked the ring, specified the weapons\nand challenged the Republican leaders\nto the combat and deserves no sym\npathy in his failure to make good. In\nhis defeat he resorts again to calling\nnames and abusive language. Of Chair\nman Hays of the Republican national\ncommittee whose testimony was given\nunder oath he says: \"I cannot believe\na single word he says.\" The statement\nthat George T. Carroll, president of the\nNew Jersey Federation of Liquor Inter\nests, was soliciting funds for the Cox\ncampaign he denies, although the let\nter signed by President Carroll is pro\nduced. This letter bears the slogan\n\"Help Elect Men Who Will Kill Pro\nhibition and contains these sentences:\n\"The nomination of Governor Cox for\nthe presidency is a big victory for\nour interests Governor\nCox is a pronounced wet.\"\n\"It is now up to our organization to\nstand unitedly behind the ticket of Cox\nand Roosevelt and roll up such, a ma\njority as will show convincingly the\npublic will 19 in our favor.\"\n\"We must have money at once to\ncarry on the work that we had planned.\nJump in and help us fight. Give as\nmuch as you can afford.\"\nGovernor Cox refuses to appear be\nfore the investigating committee and\nrelies upon his charge that all Republi\ncan managers are liars to win publie\nfavor and confidence. He starts today\nfor the West for another upheaval of\nabuse and calumny. But it will be\nstrange if those westerners, who know\na fight and a clean and effective fighter,\nenthuse over his mouthy tactics. The\nzenith of Governor Cox's career as a\ncampaigner was passed when he al\nlowed the chairman of the Democratic\nnational committee to go before the in\nvestigating committee with out a single\nfact to support his charges.\n0\nLittle Johnny Spends ;i\nc\nVm$HTiHAt\njlj\nIsland. One of the interesting things\nhe tells of his journey is that he had\n36 invitations to ride from automobil\nists, most of the offers coming from\nmotorists in Miine, New Hampshire\nand Vermont. The invitations de\ncreased as he traveled southward and\nwhile in Massachusetts and Rhode Is\nland he had practically none. Are the\nresidents of southern New England less\ncourteous or they in a greater rush, or\nboth?\nThe 10-story fall of an elevator in\nNew York this week, injuring several\npersons seriously, reminds us that de\nspite the thousands of passenger and\nfreight elevators working from one\nday's end to the other there are few\nserious accidents because of them. El\nevator construction seems to be near\nmechanical perfection for when one\nconsiders the number of people in the\ncountry using them every twenty four\nhours, the percentage of serious or\nfatal accidents proves very small.\nThe pastor of a Connecticut church\nspent his vacation on a tramping tour\nthrough New England. He traversed\nthe country from the headwaters of\nthe Connecticut to the mouth of the\nriver, making a detour through Rhode\nA Hudson Bay company predicts that\nwithin two years reindeer meat will\nbe on sale in butcher shops in all cities\nof the United States and Canada and\nbefore many more years will have sup\nplanted beef to a large extent in the\ndiet of the people. W)asn't there a\nsimilar prediction made by some con\ncern or other about whale meat a while\nagoT\nMr. Delis, the Socialist candidate,\nsays that the chief issue is the coal\nshortage. Well, the winters are mild\nin Atlanta and Uncle Sam probably\nhas got his winter's supply in for his\nvarious institutions.\nThe Tennessee- legislators are novr\ntrying to undo the suffrage ratification.\nEvidently it is not all together the\nprerogative of women to change their\nminds.\nThe law of supply and demand Hoes\nnot appear to figure in the 40,000,000\npounds of sugar a Revere sugar refin\nery is withholding from the market.\nA real September morn.\nHow hop prices do hop.\nSchool Dental Work.\n(Keene Sentinel.)\nThe extension of dental work among\nschool children and the establishment of\nclinics for their benefit is one of the\nmost practical forward steps in modern\neducation. No school system can be\ncalled complete which has not as one of\nits fundamental activities the care of the\nchildren's health and their instruction\nin the simple rules of hygiene. Foremost\nin such work comes' care of the teeth,\nfor upon their condition the entire bodily\ncondition depends to a large degree; and\nunless the body functions correctly there\ncannot be satisfactory mental activity.\nThe appointment of competent dentists\nto oversee the care of the children's\nteeth is a thing which should be neg\nlected by neither the city school authori\nties nor those of the rural districts. The\nformer are better established in this\nwork than the latter, but the need in the\ncountry is even greater than in town,\nfor dentists are not so easily reached, and\nhence tooth troubles are liable to neglect.\nThe war showed up the need for more\ngeneral work along this line. It also saw\ngreater strides made\" in it than in any\nsimilar period since time began. If the\ngood work is carried on effectively among\nthe school children, the 'new generation\nshould have a far better record and a\nhigher health percentage than any that\nlias gone before.\nessential factor, is promised by the\nrenewed activities of the railroads un\nder the impetus of increased rates of\nservice.\nfavorable conditions of agriculture\nare coupled with greatly improved in\ndustrial prospects. The prediction is\nnow? made that many plants now closed\nfor various reasons will reopen soon\nafter Labor day. We question whether\nthis statement can apply to the Amer\nican Woolen mills, for in that partic\nular line, many complex elements are\ninvolved. Wise dealers in all lines are\nrefraining from, plunging in any direc\ntion and limiting purchases to actual\nneeds of their markets. Movements of\nprices will probably rot be rapid, but\nwe must expect a downward tendency.\nEncouragement ,Js also to be found\nin the upward movement of exports\nduring July, the increase over those of\nJune being about $25,000,000. Imports\non the other hand increased only $16,\n000,000. The more other nations buy\nthe products of our industries the more\nmust our industries work.\nThe improved European war outlook\nis also helping the business situation in\nthe United States to become more\nhopeful. t As the. situation now stands,\nthe worst can be said, to 1e over and\nfrom this time on. there should be a\nconstant increase in ''public confidence.\nThe Only Way Out.\n(Rutland Herald.)\nThe Brattleboro Reformer announces\na new schedule, the paper now selling on\nthe street at 3 cents instead of 2 and the\nyearly rate being advanced to $8 or 75\ncenta a month. The, reasons: \"Advanced\ncost of paper, ink, labor, gas, power, dis\ntribution.\" Newspapers generally are\nstruggling with these factors and they\nconstitute a very real problem. The Re\nformer has been obliged to take the step\nmany others have taken before it. It's\nthe only way out.\nLeaving It To Others.\n.ii'i..\"\n(Barre Times.)\nThe automobile touring party who\nfailed to stop to ascertain the exteut of\ninjuries sustained by two motorists, who,\nas it turned out, were fatally hurt, in an\naccident near Futney but requested an\nother touring party to stop and make\ninvestigations, may have heard of the\nGolden Rule but thought it not applica\nble to themselves.\nBrightening Business Outlook.\n(Burlington Free Press.)\nThe business outlook in Vermont and\nelsewhere is growing more encouraging.\nWhile money continues difficult to se\ncure, authorities agree that the trend\nin business is toward normal and there\nfore more reassuring conditions. Abun\ndant crops are always an essential basis\nof prosperity and crop conditions\nthroughout tho United States are prom\nising. Adequate distribution, another\nPlenty of Tim. -(Barre\nTimes.)\nEven before Vermont Republicans have\nselected the state's next governor, the\nRutland News is pointing to the 1922\nelection by declaring that Judge diaries\nII. Darling of Burlington is still nursing\nan ambition to be governor of Vermont.\nMost people are concerned at .present\nover the man who is to be chief executive\nfor the next two years and will let the\n1922 choice wait for a while.\nAo f the Great Sphinx.\nThe age of the Great Sphinx In\nEgypt Is unknown, but It Is considered\nwell established that It was in exist\nence at the time of Cheops, and was\nrepaired by him earlier than the year\n300 B. C.\nA WOMAN'S BACK.\nThe Advice of This Brattleboro Woman\nis of Certain Value.\nMany a woman's back has many\naches and pains.\nOf times 'tis the kidney 's fault.\nThat's why; Doan's Kidney Pills are\nso effective. Ask your neighbor.\nMany Brattleboro women know this,\nRead, what one has to say about it\nMrs. P. G. h Colgrove, 12 Prospect\nCourt, Brattleboro, says: \"I think\nDoan's Kidney Pills are a great medi\ncine. I used them when my back and\nkidneys were in a bad condition due,\nI think, from heavy housework. My\nback was lame and sore and I couldn't\nBit down or stoop over without sharp\npains shooting through my back. My\nkidneys were weak and irregular in ac\ntion. I heard of Doan 's Kidney Pill9 so I\ngot a couple boxes and in a short time\nthey cured the attack. Since then I\nhave used Doan's as a kidney tonic and\nhave gotten excellent results.\n60c, at all dealers. Foster-Millburn\nCo., Mfrs., Buffalo, N. Y. adv.\nToday's Events\nSt. Stephen's day, the national fes\ntival of th Hungarians.\nFiftieth anniversary of the surrender\nof Sedan to the Germans.\nCentenary of the birth of Lucretia\nPcabody Hale, popular juvenile Btory\nwriter.\nThe Michigan state fair will be\nopened at Detroit today and continued\nthrough the coming week.\nGov. James H. Cox, Democratic pres\nidential nominee, is scheduled to start\ntodav on his speech-making tour of the\nWest.\nWnrren T. McCray, Republican nom\ninee for governor of Indiana, is sched\nuled to open his speaking campaign to\nday at Crawfordsville.\n\"In The Day's News.\"\nHenry Delaware Flood,' who is chair\nman of the Democratic congressional\ncommittee, is a Virginian, born in Ap\npomattox county, fifty-five years ago\ntoday. .Washington and Lee university\nlii hiV'alma mater!.' The laW is his vo\ncation. Entering political life as a\nstate legislator, he was prominent in\nbringing to pass the last constitutional\nconvention iu Virginia, and in shaping\nthe commonwealth's organic law to\nmodern demands. His service in the\nhouse of representatives dates back to\n1901, when he sat with the fifty-seventh\ncongress at its opening session, and he\nis now serving Ins tweutn consecutive\nLittle Benny's\nNote Book\nBy LEE PAPE.\nYestidday our cook Nora went to her\nsick ants funerel, so ma made the sup\npir, being stake under onions and mash\npotatoes and sumthing funny looking\nin a dish, wich ma started to put some\non pops plate and pop sed, dont give\nme eny of that, wat is that!\nIts scalloped eggplant, I jest saw the\nrecipee for it in the paper yestidday\nand 1m sure its perfeckly delicious,\nsed ma.\nI dont wunt eny, I dont like it, sed\npop, and ma sed, Now Willyum, I think\nyoure awfill, how can you tell weather\nyou like it or not? and pop sed, I have\na instinct about sutch things, and my\ninstinct tells me I dont like it.\nWell Im jest going to give you a\nlittle bit to try, you-obstinate thing,\nsod ma. And she put some on iwps\nplate and pop taisted it as if he was\ndoing it out of a sents of dooty and\nthen he taisted it agen as if he was do\ning it out of a sents of plezzurc, ma\nsaying, Wy Willyum, dont tell me that\nI see an ixpression of injoyment on\nyour face.\nIve taisted werse stuff, sed pop. Be\ning sipposed to be a compliment, and\npop ate the rest of it and passed his\nplate to ma, saying. A little more of\nthat walloped eggplant, please.\nDid you like itl sed ma.\nIt wasent so bad, sed pop, and ma\nsed, Willyum Potts, Im not going to\ngive you a bit more until you admit\nyou liked it and pop sed, O well, I\n\"dident object to it in the slightest.\nIlers your plate, sed ma handing\n4op back his plate without eny more\nscalloped egtrtvlant on it, pop saying,\nHay, wares the walloped eggplant!\nDid you like itf sed ma, and pop sed,\nO certVny T liked it, good nite, and\nma sed, Did you like it very, very\nmutch f and pop sed, Yes, yes. if I liked\nit eny more Id faint with delite.\nAll rite, heers some more, sed ma.\nAnd she put a hole pile on pops plate\nand pop ate it all with injoyable ix\npression and then looked at the dish\nagen without asking for eny more,\nproberly on account of the dish being\nempty.\nVERMONT NEWS.\nNelson Goodspeed. 81, of St. Albans\ndied at his home there Tuesday. JUr.\nGoodspeed was commissioned in 1862\nas a second lieutenant in the 13th reg\niment, Company O, Vermont Volun\nteers, and served throughout the Civil\nwar.\nA thief went into the hardware store\nof John II. Stewart on Merchants row,\nlate Sunday afternoon and, while the\nproprietor was in the rear end of the\nstore, snatched six Ingersoll watches\nand made his escape. The police were\nnotified and have) a description of the\ntman, but up to tonignt no.eiew naa\nbeen found.\nGREENFIELD FAIR THREE DAYS.\nWill Be Held Sept. 14, 15 6 Tbi\"\nYear Night Shows Also.\nThe annual Greenfield, Mass., cattle\nshow, known as the live wire fair, will\n1 held this vear Scot. 13. 14, 1\" and 16,\nterm. During the. period of the Euro- with the largest array of exhibits -and\npean war Representative Flood figured\nprominently in public affairs by virtue\nof his position as chairman of the house\ncommittee on foreign relations.\nToday's Anniversaries,\n1845 Beginning of a violent eruption\nof Mnunt TIecla. in Iceland.\n1S62 Gen. Kirby Smith advanced on does not entail a \"thinning out\" of the\nCincinnati, and martial law was entertainment program. The officials\nproclaimed in that city. of the society deliberated long upon the\n1870 The French capitulated at Sedan. question of adding another day and\n1S72 Rose Coghlan made her first ap- night, and when they finally concluded to\npearance at Wallack's theater, take the 6tep it was planned at the same\nin New York. (time not only to maintain the quality of\n1894 Moro than 500 people perished the fair program in every way, but to\nforest fires that destroyed improve it by liberal expenditures of\nthe finest entertainment program that it\nhas ever presented in its many years of\ngrowing success. For the first time the\nfair -will be run three days and three\nnights, and this innovation is expected\nto swell the attendance to above last\nyear's figures of close to 30,000.\nThe' extended duration of the fair\nFAINTING AN\nDIZZY SPELLS\nThe Cause of such Symptoms\nand Remedy Told in This\nLetter.\nSyracuse, N. Y. \"When- X.- com\nmenced the Change of Life I war poorly,\nbad no appetite and\nhad fainticg spells.\nI Buffered for two\nor three yt'r be\nfore I bcgantaklng\nLydia E.; Pink bam'\nVegetable Com\npound and the' Liver\nPills which I law ad\nvertised i a t h e\nf tapers and in ycur\nittle books. I tcok\nabout twelve bottles\nof your VcKtabie\nCompound and found it a wonderful\nremedy. I commenced to pick up at\nonce and my suffering was relieved. I\nliavo told others about your medicine\nand know of some who Lave taken it.\nI am glad to help others all I can.\"\nMrs. R. E. Deming, 437 W. Lafayetia\nAve., Syracuse, N. Y.\nWhile Change of Life is a most crit\nical period of a woman's existence, the\nannoying symptoms which accompany\nit may be controlled, and normal health\nrestored by the timely use of Lydia E.\nPinkham'a Vegetable Compound.\nMoreover this reliable remedy con\ntains no narcotics or harmful drugs and\nowes its efficiency to tke- medicinal ex\ntractives of the native roots and hcrba\nwiiicli it contains.\nCOMB SAGE TEA\nINTO GRAY HAIR\nPfPI\nthen\nLadies! Try. this t Darkens beautifully\nand nobody can tell Brings back\nIts gloss and youtbf nlness.\nCommon garden sage brewed into a\nheavy tea, with sulphur and alcohol add\ned, will turn gray, streaked and faded\nhair beautifully dark and luxuriant.\nMixing the Sage Tea and Sulphur recipe\nat home, though, is troublesome. An\neasier way is to get the ready-to-use\npreparation improved by the addition\nof other ingredients a large bottle, at\nlittle cost, at drug stores, known as\n\"Wyeth's Sage and Sulphur Com\npound,\" thus avoiding a lot of mflss\".\nWhile gray, faded hair is not sinful,\nwe all desire to retain our youthful ap\npearance and attractiveness. By dark\nr&ng your hair with Wyeth's Sage and\nSulphur Compound, no one can tell, be\ncause it does it so naturally, so evenly.\nYou just dampen a sponge or soft brush\nwith it and draw this through your hair,\ntaking one small strand at a time; by\nmorning all gray hairs have disappeared.\nAfter another application or two your\nhair becomes beautifully dark, glossy,\nsoft and luxuriant and you appear years\nyounger. Adv.\nPUTNEY.\nBurial of F. M. Lewis.\nThe body of Franklin M. Lewis was\nbrought here for burial Tuesday morn\ning. Rev. Mr. Curtis of Westminster\nWest officiated in the absence of the\ncommunity pastor, Rev. J. W. Crippen.\nMr. Lew.is, who was born at Wells\nNov17, 1838, died at his home in West\nHaven, Conn., where the funeral .was\nheld Monday nfternoon, the body being\nbrought to Putney for burial in the\nfamily lot in Mount Pleasant cemetery.\nThe three Rons. Elma C. of West Haven,\nWilliam M. of Brattleboro and Frank\nH. of Jersey City, and the two grandsons,\nHarold E. of West Haven and Gordon of\nJersey City, accompanied the body here.\nother towns in\n1895\n1908-\n111\nHinckley and\nMinnesota.\n-General celebration in Germany\nof the twenty-fifth anniversary\nof the fall of Sedan.\nmoney to secure the best of attractions\nand enough of them to keep the crowds\namused and instructed every moment\nfrom the opening of the fair Monday\nevening, Sept. 13, to sundown Thursday\nMarv Russell Charpiot, who evening, Sept. lt.\nfounded one of the first homes I A summary of the attractions at the\nfor intemperate women in Amer-'live wire fair includes superior exhibits\nica. died in Boston. Born in Ire-'of purebred cattle, bloodd horses, sheep,\nland, Aug. 15, 1S30. swine, poultry and pet stock, two exhibi-\n1916 The heads of tho four railway turn halls crowded with products of home\nbrotherhoods revoked the order and garden, an extensive\nMiss Ethel Buckman of Bellows Falls\nwas a guest of her cousin, Mrs. L. JJ.\nBugbee, a short time the lat of the\nweek, returning home Sunday.\nMARLBORO.\nMiss Hat tie Braman'is spending the\nweek with Mr. and Mrs. J, H. Hamilton.\nMiss Pauline Shaw of Brattleboro is\nvisiting her grandparents at the parson\nage this week.\nMaster Chester Shaw, who spent last\nweek at the parsonage, went to his home\nin Brattleboro Sunday,\nMrs. Minnie Prouty and son.\" Reuben,\nof Brattleboro are spending the week\nwith. Rev. and Mrs. H. II: fcjiiaw.\nThe ladies' sale Aug. 25 was a sitcoess,\na large number being present. Mrs. Julia\nfor a r.atinal railroad strike.\nOne Year Ago. Today.\nNew Zealand ratified t he peace treaty.\nAllies lifted the blockade against\nHungary.\nToday's Birthdays.'\nGeorge R. Sims,\" celebrate\ndramatist, novelist, and journalist\n73 years ago today.\nHenrietta Crosman, a' well-known ac\ntress of the American stage, born at\nWheeling, W. Va., 50 years ago today.\nHiram W. Johnson, California sen\nator and late candidate for the Repub\nlican presidential nomination, born at\nSacramento, Calif., 54 years ago today.\nHoke Smith, who is now contesting\nfor renomination as United States sen\nator from Georgia born at Newton, N.\nC, 65 years ago today.\n1 \"WARDSBORO CENTER. t\nBer,t Bacon. is staving a .few days\nat DiTiaSiriith's.', v f\nSchool began Monday with Mrs.\nMerle Putnam as teacher.\nMr. Brown 's household goods have\narrived. ,The family is expected this\nweek.\nGordon Roberts carried. William Fitz\npatrick and son, Archie, to Brattleboro\nAug. 25, to meet Mabel Fitzpatrick.\nMr. and Mrs. Nahor Sage and Mr.\nand Mrs. Merle Putnam- were in New\nfane Aug. 29 to attend the 55th wed\nding anniversary of Mr. and. Mrs. H.\nA. Carpenter.'\nDr. Hopkinson and Dr.Thomas op\nerated on Marion Putnam, Willie Put\nnam, Gerald Shine and Charlotte Rob\nerts Friday at Merle Putnam's. They\nhad tonsils and adenoids removed. All\nare doing welL -t\nshow, a big exhibit of fish and game by\nthe Massachusetts fish and game com\nmission, harness racing for $u,000 in\npurses, the finest program of vaudeville\nand special amusement attractions ever\nseen on Franklin park, music\" by two\nautomobile John.son. tha oldest woman in town, at\nlenueu, ui? sale.\nMr. and Mrs. E. P. Adams enter\ntained several relatives and friends Sun\nday, among .whom were Mr. and 'Mrs.\nLeon Adams of Boston.\nSunday, Sept. 5, will be observed as\nwell-known military, bands, one of the music day. The service, which will begin\nlargest midways at any New England (at 11 o'clock will be largely musical. It\nd English 'fflir' \"ancing m a big open air pavilion! is expected that Professor Haas of Ames\nn 4 1. n.-..4 .....Ann nVfiliAfitna C rt rla?ll..l.!ll 211 1\nborn tuiHinuuun wLinfutt uBii, uiius juui win presiue at ine organ ana inat\n\"P7rt. Ftlmn Allen, and thfl larortnt. li-, frnm Amue hill idIII o..'.t\nplay of ordnance and small arms, both\nancient and modern, ever seen outside of\na United States arsenal.\nNearly all beautiful things are expen\nincluding women.\nIf\"\nEl\nLI\nft\n8\nij\nFull of Food Value\nNourishing; ready:-cooked,\nh economical. c i-k v pi v h r v\n:A sugar saver, because\ncontains its own sugar\nYou 11 enjoy the convenience\nand the sweet, appealing fla\nvor of this wheat and bar\nley food.\ni\ni\ni.","height":"32316","width":"26252"}}
